#include <libxml/parser.h>
#include <libxml/tree.h>

void main() {
    xmlDocPtr doc;
    xmlNodePtr root;

    // Create a simple XML document
    doc = xmlNewDoc(BAD_CAST "1.0");
    root = xmlNewNode(NULL, BAD_CAST "root");
    xmlNodeAddContent(root, BAD_CAST "This is the root node");
    xmlDocSetRootElement(doc, root);

    // Free the document
    xmlFreeDoc(doc);
}

The test program is a simple XML parser test. It creates an XML document and then frees it. The program is expected to pass, but it actually fails with a non-zero exit code.

The issue here is that the program is using the `xmlFreeDoc()` function to free the document, but this function is not sufficient to free all the memory allocated by the document. Specifically, the `xmlNewNode()` function allocates memory for the node, but this memory is not freed by `xmlFreeDoc()`.



